<h2>Position</h2>

<p>Also very useful, but takes a bit more to explain.  There are several types of positioning: relative, static (the default), absolute, and fixed.</p>

<div class="annotated-code">
  <pre class="prettyprint linenums lang-css">
.wrapper {
	position: relative;
	margin: 0 auto;
	height: 150px;
	width: 300px;
}

.relative-shift {
	position: relative;
	left: 10px;
	top: 10px;
}

.bottomright {
	position: absolute;
	bottom: 10px;
	right: 10px;
}
</pre>
  <div class="annotation" data-line="2">
    Relative: Positioned relative to its position it would have otherwise had
  </div>
  <div class="annotation" data-line="3">
    0 auto: a clever way of centering a div (as it effectively says 0 top/bottom margin and as much left/width margin as possible, i.e. centered)
    Make sure you specify a width for it though.
  </div>
  <div class="annotation" data-line="10">
    top/right/bottom/left give you ways of shifting it relative to where it would have otherwise (for position: relative)
  </div>
  <div class="annotation" data-line="15">
    absolute is relative to the first (non-static) container tag
  </div>
  <div class="annotation" data-line="16">
    top/right/... refer to how many pixels in between the border of the container tag and the element on that side
  </div>
</div>

